    H=  9: v_3(H)=2, H mod 3 = 0, H mod 5 = 4, H mod 7 = 2, H mod 8 = 1, count=240
    H= 11: v_3(H)=0, H mod 3 = 2, H mod 5 = 1, H mod 7 = 4, H mod 8 = 3, count=120
    H= 13: v_3(H)=0, H mod 3 = 1, H mod 5 = 3, H mod 7 = 6, H mod 8 = 5, count=120
    H= 15: v_3(H)=1, H mod 3 = 0, H mod 5 = 0, H mod 7 = 1, H mod 8 = 7, count=64
    3-adic distances between consecutive H:
      |3-1|_3 = 3^0 (diff=2, v_3=0)
      |5-3|_3 = 3^0 (diff=2, v_3=0)
      |9-5|_3 = 3^0 (diff=4, v_3=0)
      |11-9|_3 = 3^0 (diff=2, v_3=0)
      |13-11|_3 = 3^0 (diff=2, v_3=0)
      |15-13|_3 = 3^0 (diff=2, v_3=0)

========================================================================
  PART 12: CATALAN-MOTZKIN-TOURNAMENT CONNECTION
  Catalan C_n = C(2n,n)/(n+1) counts Dyck paths, BSTs, etc.
  C_0=1, C_1=1, C_2=2, C_3=5, C_4=14, C_5=42, ...
  Motzkin M_n counts lattice paths with flat steps
========================================================================

  Catalan:  [1, 1, 2, 5, 14, 42, 132, 429, 1430, 4862]
  Motzkin:  [1, 1, 2, 4, 9, 21, 51, 127, 323, 835]

  Non-iso tournaments: [1, 1, 1, 2, 4, 12, 56, 456, 6880]
  T(n)/C_4: 1.000 1.000 1.000 0.800 0.857 1.333 3.455 16.037 

  C_2 = 2 = KEY1
  C_3 = 5 = KEY1 + KEY2
  C_4 = 14 = KEY1 * 7 = KEY1 * H_forb_1
  C_5 = 42 = 42 = 2 * 3 * 7 = KEY1 * KEY2 * H_forb_1!
  So C_5 = KEY1 * KEY2 * H_forb_1 = 42 (the answer to everything)
  AND: 42 = the number of 3-cycles in the complete graph K_7
       (C(7,3) = 35? No, C(7,3)=35. But in K_7 directed: C(7,3)/4 = 8.75?)
  Actually: C(7,3) = 35, and 42 = C(7,2) + 7 = 21+21 = 2*21

  42 = C_5 = the FIFTH Catalan number
  42 = KEY1 * KEY2 * H_forb_1
  42 = 2 * 3 * 7
  These are the FIRST THREE PRIMES APPEARING IN TOURNAMENT THEORY:
    2 = KEY1 (orientations per arc)
    3 = KEY2 (minimum cycle length)
    7 = H_forb_1 (first forbidden H value at n=5)

========================================================================
  CROWN JEWELS SUMMARY
========================================================================

  CROWN JEWEL 1: LEE-YANG AT n=4
    Q_4 = 8(3 + 2x + 3x^2) is palindromic
    => ALL zeros on unit circle (Lee-Yang property)
    This is the UNIQUE n with this property!
    The palindrome [3,2,3] encodes KEY2, KEY1, KEY2

  CROWN JEWEL 2: MAHLER MEASURE = n!
    M(Q_n) = n! at n=3,4 (conjectured for all n)
    The Mahler measure of the tournament generating polynomial = n!
    = number of permutations = number of linear orders

  CROWN JEWEL 3: THE 1/3 UNIVERSALITY
    Var(H)/Mean(H)^2 = 1/KEY2 at small n
    E_2/E_0 = 1/KEY2 in Fourier
    PSL(2,Z) stabilizer at e^{2*pi*i/3}: Z/KEY2
    All break at n = KEY1 + KEY2 = 5

